Site:02<br>
The Training<br>
<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp My mother and the nurse were watching close for any signs of sickness.  “Nurse, is he ok?”… <br>
“He’ll be fine…you don’t have to worry about it.  I gave him his shot, he should be fine for quite a while.”  I was listening to the conversation, while trying to get up on the bed, and sit upright.  It all sounded like gibberish to me for some reason… I couldn’t get why…?  <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I felt really drowsy.  Once my mom and the nurse stopped speaking I took my food that I hadn’t eaten in some time and started to drink some orange juice.  I took the small batch of peas that were on the plate and started to chew on them.  They were really bad.  I didn’t want to eat it, but I was so hungry that I ate everything on the plate.  I began to feel better, and a little bit stronger.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I felt like I was changing…  I told my mom how I felt, and she said that it was just a stage I was going through.  Heh, I thought that I went through “that” change already. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “All you need is a little bit of sleep.”  She said, while giving me a gleeful grin.  Two weeks later the doctor said that I can now get out and do a little bit of exercise, but not too much because I had an almost healed knee and a swollen ankle.  At around 6:00 P.M. I left the hospital and finally headed for home.  When I got back into the dump, I went strait to my room and laid on the bed…feeling the comfort of being back.  The place was practically different to me, since I had been gone for so long and all.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I had sat down on my chair and leaned on to the corner of my small, but efficient, desk to draw anything that came on my mind.  For a while I thought about that day at the hospital.  How did I do it?  It’s like… I saw what was going to happen.  I got up from the rough wooden chair and went to my house to get something to drink.  When I got there my mother was there.  She was making something in a big pot of water.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Mom….” I had said in a low voice.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Yes? …What is it son?” She said in a kind of rough voice.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “One day at the hospital… A man started to choke an old lady.” I explained to her.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Well, I’m not bringin’ you there anymore.”  She said as if I had just told a joke.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “I had a vision a few minutes before it happened… It was blurry so I’m not too sure what it was.  I think that it was a man struggling to get up, after being beat down into the floor, and an old lady trying to breath.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Well, that’s a coincidence.” She looked at me for a second and then back at the pot to stir whatever was inside it.  “You know… your father had a little ability.  That’s why he took him away.”  She said in a strange voice.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Him…?  Who is… him?” I asked while heading to the refrigerator.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “God, my son.”  She went to a cabinet reaching for something.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I grabbed a packaged drink and began to walk back to my room.  “Ability?” I muttered under my breath.  Back at my room I was sitting down in my chair, thinking about what my mother had told me.  “Ah, there we go.  I got it!”  I finally thought of something to draw.  “A few strands of hair over here… a little shading here…” As I was about to finish my drawing, my mother came into my room as quietly as she could.  I guess she wasn’t trying to disturb me.  She sat down on my bed and started to do these strange little things with her hands.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Your father taught me this little trick.”  She said while she suddenly began to break a sweat.  Out of nowhere this little light shone on top of her hand.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Whoa! What’s that!?” I said with my eyes open wide.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Go on, touch it.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “No! Not until you tell me what it is!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Don’t worry about it…it’s just a light.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “…? Umm… ok.”  I began to get close to it, and the closer I got the brighter the light grew.  When I tried to touch it, my hand wet right through it.  “Hey, I can’t touch it…”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “I know, it’s meant to be a natural light… the more human energy it feels the more it shines” She said as if she was a teacher or something.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “How did you do that?” I said with my eyes still wide.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “It’s just hand motions your father taught me.  You can learn this, and much more.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “How… how do I do it?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “You know, to you it is all much simpler than me.  It’s all in your head.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “In my head? … You mean you know!?” I said with my eyes wider than before.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Yes, I knew ever since you were born.  There’s no way to change it.  It’s in your genes.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “So you mean that all the visions I’ve been having… Those are all…umm… techniques?  But not all of them were what you think!” My voice grew louder.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Yes, I know… The ability I told you your father had, he was able to see the future.  In his visions he also saw people dressed in white and black uniforms doing special techniques called Evaniques.  The name comes from special beings that used to live on earth.  Your father told me a story that I won’t quite get on right now.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “I see, so if I see some sort of different visions than the ones that I usually get then… those are…?”  As I finished my sentence my mother left my room and went for the kitchen.  I thought to myself “Why…? How…?”<br>
<br>
